column1: When will the UK have vaccinated 80% or more of its 18 and over population with a full course of a COVID-19 vaccine?
column5: ['Before 1 July 2021', 'Between 1 July 2021 and 31 July 2021', 'Between 1 August and 31 August 2021', 'Between 1 September 2021 and 30 September 2021', 'Not before 1 October 2021']
column6: ['Technology', 'Health']
42,379,353 as of 26th August
Counting 42,087,971 today, leaving 224,065 to the target. At the current rate of just over 100,000 per day, this should resolve this weekend. Maybe Monday, given the lower weekend numbers.
Counting 41,673,647 today. Still on pace for August 27th.

Given the new numbers in question above, 42.3m is the 80pc threshold. With 40.97m already vaccinated this means 1.3m are left. Over 10 days remaining reporting this is 130k per day. Rates are remaining at 160k per day, so well within end August timeframe
I count 41,204,255 using the new sources on August 20. It still appears this should resolve next week.

The change in numerator from the original source alters my forecast slightly (the original data included 16-17 year old in the numerator, which is now being manually removed by the update on August 19th).
This may be getting a bit interesting again: increase of yesterday only 0.2
At current run rate (from 70 to 75% was 16 days) it should be well within August

Major revision of my forecast. The last week hasn't really shown much slowdown and its been pretty steady for the past month, so expecting a major swing in the next 2 weeks is unlikely. Still allowing a small chance for an upset, but unlikely with current numbers.
Finally decided to settle fully on the August finish.
40,206,029 as of Aug 12. 7 day average 165.5k. Puts it 12 days out or Aug 24. Barring disaster it looks almost certain to be before Aug 31 now.

Humming right along I see. We are about 2,210,000 from the goal with 20 days remaining. Average is approximately 160,000 per day at the moment and so that puts us at 14 days of reporting to hit the 80% threshold. Expected value of August 31 (accounting for a slight drop in averages) is 850,000 in excess of the required 42,230,000.
Still on track for August 25.
Number jumped to 75.7 (+0.4), it seems settled, going to 98% for August bucket

Second dose daily rates have remained fairly steady for the past month or so, with maybe a tiny decrease. Estimating about 0.28-0.29% per day. Since it's been so steady, I'm inclined to think it'll persist for at least the next few weeks.
Now at 75.3pc or 39.8m with second dose.
Joining the party a little late in the game.
I know, Iillustrated my expectation on which I build my forecast opinion.

Thank you @paulm @probahilliby @GMR for your helpful comments. First, going against *this* crowd seems a bit too courageous (= foolish). Especially after I ran I model with taking first shots from 8 weeks earlier (I didn't know in UK the interval between shots was that long) – in this case, we would have 82.4 % on August 31. I am humbly reverting to the crowd’s mean and will keep on looking out for signs if the 8 week or the 5 week model performs better…. (if the effect of 5 weeks earlier is >40% and the effect of 8 weeks earlier <60%, 80% won’t be reached before September).
I would presume that the rate has to drop by almost a quarter in the next 3 weeks for September to be reached.

August seems very unlikely. The 2nd dose increase equals pretty much the 1st dose increase 5 weeks earlier. Thus the 2nd dose increase from August 10 to August 31 will probably correspond to the 1st dose increase from July 6 and July 27, which was 2.1 points. So, 75.0+2.1= 77.1 would be the quick and dirty prediction for end of August. Not even sure if 80% is secured for September … @belikewater @paulm @probahilliby : Is this potential wisdom against the crowd or just foolish oversimplification?
It's going to be close and the rate is going down but it's harder for me to motivate it getting slower than picking up again in the remaining time. So I will stick to August over September.

Current daily rate puts this at about 28th August, with a slight uptick in daily rate when looking at the last 28 days. However I expect the rate will slow down as it gets closer to 80%, such that I think an early to mid September is more likely.
Geepers this is going to be a tight one. I reckon we should get there on the 27th. Need to stay above 121k average so should be sitting nice

The increase is about 0.3 pp per day at the moment, which would mean ~20 days until we hit 80%. Today is the 8th, so that puts the expectation at around the 28th. Things may slow down though, I think the crowd is overly confident here.
Following the crowd as can't find actual dates when the second dose will be available.
UK take-up, mostly amongst young adults, is plateauing.

I am expecting an erratic daily rate from now on due to drop-offs through holidays and deferrals, but expecting this to be offset by increased bookings seen via the climb in first doses through the first three weeks of June. The advantages of double-vaccinations for travelling abroad should also help encourage continued uptake. A fall to 150K moving av. this week is OK if the rate stays within 10-12% of the June levels, which would be within the margins seen last month. But it will be close. A lot will now depend on how those factors play out; if the drop-offs are too severe we could still miss the end of August deadline. I'm still with earlier forecast of 26th-30th and holding my breath.
Rate is slipping behind a little bit. Now on track for August 26. There's still 5 days of play, but need to watch the next week closely.

Yes, the current rate takes it to August 26 or 27 and has consistently been so, but there is a remarkable slow in the rate that may take it to September; furthermore, the slowing is consistent with the lag between first and second doses, it seems, which could indicate that the September bin is becoming an increasingly likely landfall for an 80% landfall.

7,14 and 21-day averages 160-170k daily doses therefore suggests on track for August. My forecast model suggests 27/28th of August to hit target if at 150-160k p/day to build in a buffer from averages
Numbers still holding strong to complete in August. Checking back in a couple weeks. 160,000 per day is above the 140,000 or so we need to complete this in August.
3% every 10 days looks like the current pace, on track for around August 26th. But any small decline in the rate puts it in the next bucket so there's a decent chance it misses August.
Still on track for August 24th
Needs to stay above 140k/day
Forecast mostly in line with my last updated model. Increasing the chance of August
It's not going to happen. Too much antivaxx, too many people living underground.

37,962k as of July 29. 7 Day avg 169,458. Current rate puts it 25 days out or Aug 23. Noting that it has slowed in the last week but I'm getting a bit nervous that the populace is behaving better than I anticipated (which is a good thing, but doesn't help my forecast). Broadly speaking uptake has been surprisingly consistent. Needs to be <126k/day for my forecast to hold so I'm moving to it being more likely before Sept 1
Updating as I had failed at basic arithmetic in my last prediction

First doses only hit 80% in mid-June. Assuming all of those people have to wait the full 8 weeks, it's not actually possible to get to 80% second doses before the end of August, but I'm hedging because the majority seem to think August is likely.
british news say 170K/day second dose with 5.2 million people to reach 80% as of july 29
Now at 71.1pc or 37.6m with second dose.
As at 27/7 uk vaccinated is 71.1%. Daily increase of around 0.3%. IF this continues 80% will be reached by late August.

Adding 5% to making it happen in August. Approximately 4,929,000 people left to get to the 80% threshold and current numbers are averaging 160,000-170,000 which is above the 142,000 average needed that I calculated 10 days ago. They really are maintaining pace on people showing up for their second dose, so I don't see why we would miss it unless something crazy happened.

As of Jul 24, the full course uptake was 70.3%. To get to 80%, we need another 9.7% uptake. Historically over the past 4 weeks, the daily uptake has been almost flat, with an average of 0.32% / day (actually accelerating a bit to about 0.33% in the past week). To get to 80% by Jul 31, that will require the uptake to grow to over 1.39% / day, more than 4 times the historical rate. Setting the probability of that to 0. Continuing at the current rate of 0.32% / day, it is expected to get to 80% on Aug 23. In order to get to 80% on or after Sep 1st, the daily rate will need to go down to below 0.25%, about 78% of it's historical rate. Looking at the first dose uptake, it hasn't slowed down until the first dose uptake was around 84%. So I'm assuming that the second dose also won't slow down significantly. Still, leaving 10% probability of it slowing down enough to get to 80% in early September.
I think he target will be reached on the 16th of August plus or minus 5 days

As of Jul 25, the full course uptake was 69.9%. To get to 80%, we need another 10.1% uptake. Historically over the past 4 weeks, the daily uptake has been almost flat, with an average of 0.31% / day (actually accelerating a bit to about 0.34% in the past 10 days). To get to 80% by Jul 31, that will require the uptake to grow to over 1.6%/day, more than 5 times the historical rate. Setting the probability of that to 0. Continuing at the current rate of 0.31% / day, it is expected to get to 80% on Aug 25. In order to get to 80% on or after Sep 1st, the daily rate will need to go down to below 0.26%, about 86% of it's historical rate. Looking at the first dose uptake, it hasn't slowed down until the first dose uptake was around 84%. So I'm assuming that the second dose also won't slow down significantly. Still, leaving 10% probability of it slowing down enough to get to 80% in early September.
Still on track for August 23rd, giving 8 days of play out of the 39 days remaining in the third bin.
Vaccinations still outpacing my original forecast, and mostly in line when I correct my forecast with a extra fudge factor. See https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1308115
Given on June 2 there was 50.7% and 26.4M fully vaccinated. This can be extrapolated to a target of 41.7M fully vaccinated persons to hit 80% (we'll assume the population change isn't a factor).

So, from Thursday 22 July, vaccination uptake will be updated to use the mid-2020 population estimates. Which was slightly higher than mid-2019... This could affect the outcome, and is the sort of thing that tends to happen when questions are going according to forecast... According to ONS: https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/populationandmigration/populationestimates/timeseries/gbpop/pop UK population increased by ~0.42% mid-2019 to mid-2020, so perhaps the vaccination data we are reviewing will be adjusted to 99.57% of current totals? I had allowed for 4 days drift for unknowns, but had not expected this one. I think there is room, but will look to see impact on % uptake on 22nd.
Now at 68.8pc or 36.2m with second dose.

Increased my August probability due to current rate - need over 140k/day to reach target currently over 170k/day Current 2nd vaccine wait time is 8 weeks - 80% +8weeks is 11 Aug Govt is asking the Joint Committee on Vaccination and Immunisation (JCVI) to provide urgent advice on halving the interval from eight weeks to four weeks https://www.mylondon.news/news/london-covid-vaccine-wait-time-21022688 This would make over 88% of the 18+ population eligible to receive their vaccine before the end of August. Unlikely that the JCVI will drop to 4 weeks though because 8 weeks is best for protection https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/covid-19-vaccine-gap-doses-four-weeks-immunisation-nadhim-zahawi-1098474
Still on pace for August 22nd.

We are now a few days ahead of expected forecast 26th Aug-2nd Sept, and the running av. still on track in July. I'm expecting some fluctuations over next few weeks as the holiday season and recent news about easing restrictions may affect schedules, but expecting a 7-day av. 155-185K to be maintained overall. Anticipating a marginal increase in next two weeks to reflect the increasing rate of 1st doses late May, as 8-wk gaps between doses become the norm; if all goes well this will provide a slight buffer against missed appointments and other drop-offs. This may be critical, as I expect more variance in August due to holidays. I'm looking for other warning signs that rates may drop, but I still think the issues with Delta cases, and the requirement for full doses to travel should be enough to keep encouraging people continuing with second doses as booked. Target date range 23th August - 30th August.

Running the numbers one more time on this. Approx. 6,673,000 people still need to get 2nd dose to hit 80% and the daily average right now is around 161,000. There are 47 days of reporting remaining and we need 142,000 average in order to make it before 9/1 deadline. Basic math says we should make it in 42 days if the average holds and people keep their appointments.
35,543k as of July 16. 7 Day average still holding. I'll hold too.
Latest vaccination data (67.1% on the 14th july) overtaking my already accelerated forecast (see comment https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1308115)

As of 7/15/2021 around 35M have been fully vaccinated with around 7M to go to reach 80% (approx. 42M). Using the latest 7-day average of 2nd doses of around 163K the UK should the 80% mark right around 8/27/2021. Factors such as increased fear of Delta could increase the vaccination rate while vaccine hesitancy could bring it down.
slight move up in confidence as the second dose uptake rates are slightly beating expectation.
Vaccinations rates are faster than my model (see previous forecast comment).

My forecast is based on the lag between first dose and second dose rates. It appears the numbers so far are lagged by about 10 weeks. Given the first dose hit 80% on June 16th, that would lead to second dose hitting 80% around August 25th. I'm reserving some probability in the later brackets to account for schedule slippage and conversion failure.
Anyone who has not been vaccinated at this point has made a decision not to be vaccinated. These goals are not realistic.
Not sure I should have diverted so much from Sept.

So it's a month on since my first look at this and I'd say that things are still on track for a August finish on the 80%. second doses given so far this month have been very consistent in numbers pushing towards a 45 day finishline from now (25/26 Aug) . I was concerned about the potential for the summer holiday break to potentially delay the process however given the recent change in government attitude on quarentines it seems likely that what delays that do happen will be overtaken by people bringing vaccination dates forwards. further discusison about shortening time between vaccinations back to manufacturer guidance seems to indicate a potential for a sooner target date but still in August, daily rate for 2nd doses needs to be over 350k per day to complete before the end of this month ( which is possible from an infrastructure perspective ) which is an effective doubling of the current run rate, unlikely to occur.
34,541k as of July 9, 7 day average ~160k and holding puts it 47 days out or still Aug 25. Still holding forecast

Given eight week gap between first and second jab, 80% cannot be reached before around 8th August. Current r/r for second doses around 160k-170k which implies 80% reached in last week of August. Monitor - r/r appears to be slowing significantly.
Now at 64.9pc or 34.2m with second dose.

We are aiming for around 42,216,000 with 34,027,000 completed as of today. Current average daily around 160,000 which leads to a simple outcome of 51 days to complete the vaccination. This is assuming no slowdown in the rate of vaccinations. 51 days from today is 8/27/21 which would end up leaving 4 days of cushion.

Stronger forecast based on current rate of vaccination, move to 8-10w between doses, time past since current % and same % at first dose all pointing to August. UK want to open up and go back to 'normal' meaning people will be more anxious to finalise their vaccinations. All looking positive. I want to go higher but am wary of overconfidence

Wondering how previously infected (~7,5% of population) play a role in the statistic. As far as I can tell, giving a single shot as a "booster" is widely considered sufficient at this point, although a second dose is recommended. I believe that those with a single booster would then not be considered "fully vaccinated", pushing the date quite a lot in the future.
Vaccination pace has slowed down. At the current rate, it will take around 50-55 days to reach 80%, which is around the last week of August.
Increasing my August probability based on current numbers

Looking at the latest % of 2 doses it seems like are speeding up a little compared to my forecast model described below. The error now is +1.3%. I guess the second doses are finally been done early with a shorter gap?
33.4 M are fully vaccinated. pace is slowing, average over 7 days around 160k-170k. still most likely to finish in July based on rate and conditions
33,402k a/o July 3; 7 day avg ~165k/day; 8,754k to go means 53 days at current rate or Aug 25 which is steady with last week so I'll hold the line

My current forecast model of 2nd vaccinations is doing alright this past week. It assumes that the 2nd doses done on the June 25 are the same as the 1st doses done on April 7; then it adds the daily average increase from 11+ weeks past to 61.2% (value on June 25)

32.8M have now had 2nd dose leaving 9.2ish left to have theirs. rate of vaccination of 200k per day but trending downward. at 200k per day it would take 46 days to complete 80% which puts us in the middle of August.
Revised estimate. Daily 2nd dose shots have halved since my previous forecast. At current rate of 2nd doses, need about another 68-75 days from now.

It's still a close call, and could well tip into September, but I do expect 2nd dose rates to start to climb from this week on, as the 12wk interval gradually phases out (linked to the 1st dose decline in late March), and we move towards an 8-9wk gap.
32,460k a/o June 26 (61.6%). Rate is still slowing (7day avg is 162,868).

Now that 80-85% of adults have been vaccinated is a matter of understanding when these second doses will be administered. News of first dose vaccine is irrelevant (i am assuming people show up to their second dose).

It will be tight, but a few factors now support the end of August (just): The gap was originally 11weeks, measured at the dates reaching 50% for both vaccines. End of August would be ~10 wks. But many dates for the second jab can or have now been brought forward to 8 wks. There are also ‘Grab a jab’ clinics for younger people, and higher than expected uptake by under 25s. In a few few weeks almost all capacity can go to second doses, which will help shift the rate upwards. Still seems possible and the political will is encouraging. Edit: In fact, forget the political will; I think the population is taking it upon itself to be cautious due to the rapid influx of Delta, and the effects on travel over Summer.
Now over 80pc with 1st dose. 60pc at second dose with about 250k extra people per day
Correction, just read comment by Dodohjk (although I just read 80% figure achieved on 17.06.). So slight possibility of August.

Five days ago 80% have had their 1st dose. There's a lag of 3 months so you would expect roughly 20.09.2021 for the same rate of 2nd doses. However, not everybody is getting the 2nd dose (according to polls and experience in e.g. Israel), which might push the date to October. Don't see how this could be achieved before September unless J&J/Biontech have a greater share than I remember them having (weirdly can't find a quick overview of ratios).

So far, more than 43 million people have had a first vaccine dose - about 80% of the adult population - and almost 32 million have had a second. An average of about 176,000 second doses are now being given a day, with the delivery of second doses accelerated in response to the emergence of the Delta variant, first identified in India.
Looks like the slope might be following first doses lowering the odds of July.
60% second dose was reached on the 22 June; 60% first dose was reached on the 5 April; there were 78 days in between. 80% first dose was reached on the 16 June; +78 days it is 2 September.

At current run rate, suggests 80% reached in mid August. Progress slowing however, and increased focus on 1st doses for all adults? 80% first dose reached in mid June; also suggests mid August reached for 2nd dose. Review weekly - could well be wrong on this but I think we'll see substantial slowing in next few weeks.

31,449,915 out of ~42,120k (80%) done as of June 20th which is the 60% point where the 1st dose rate slowed. 7 day average for fully vaccinated dropped to 210,887 as of June 20th from 292,212 June 13th and 340,303 June 6th so it seems the uptake rate is slowing. Current rate puts 80% 51 days away or August 11th so that should be plenty of time to get the stragglers unless the rate really hits a wall. I'm more optimistic than a week ago but there's still a serious risk it could fall into Sept.

UK are expecting to hit 2/3rds fully vaccinated by 19 July - 75 days after they hit 66% with the first jab assuming the same rate 75 days after 80% on 16 June will be 30 Aug. Have increased August probability slightly but will increase more if current trends continue as I suspect that they will continue to reduce the booster wait time
My bro who is v.early 20s has his 2nd on Sept 3, increasingly confident in August

We hit 80% of first-dose uptake on 6/16. Given the 8-week delay between that and the second dose appointment, it seems like the basic estimated number should be 8/11. That leaves 20 days of August to complete the vaccinations which should be plenty of time for the UK to get to 80% in that timeframe. Still not 100% convinced on this and there is more of a chance of slowing down than speeding up, so I've left a small window for the next month and will update if new information arises.

End of August still looks plausible, even if the rate of 2nd doses declines as 1st doses did through the second half of March. But I think a few factors could marginally improve the schedule. The delta variant is now widespread. Second jabs for over 40s can now be brought forward to 8 weeks (over 50s and 'at risk' groups were already eligible). The entire adult population should have completed first jabs by 19th July - in line with the delayed lockdown easing - so there are strong political as well as health incentives to get the first round complete by then. In early July there should be increasing availability for the second doses as first doses taper off, which suggests other age groups will also be able to bring the date forward. Some groups may have this gap reduced further, but likely still in August. So a potential for 80% by mid-end August.

Big swing from Sep to august due to changes this week. I expect 1st dose people to go to very low level by 1st August at current rate or above. At this point all doses go to 2nd doses and the current 8-12 week dose gap will reduce to the recommended 3-4 weeks for pfizer and unknown but shorter for AZ should be at 80% in August but have stayed in 60:40 range for now

At some point yesterday the 80% first dose threshold was reached, we would expect to hit ~84% by the end of the month. From my initial forecast I said that doses may be brought forward for age groups that matter for the purpose of this question (<30). That has now happened, and if everyone was to come forward for their second dose between 8/9 weeks we would be done by 12th August. However I still think it's unlikely that will happen as it assumes: 1. Everyone who got a first dose will get a second 2. Everyone who gets a second will get it at the earliest opportunity
re adjust for the chance that they will let everyone go to 8 weeks, not just 40plus

I completely stuffed up my last forecast by forgetting the 8 to 12 week gap between vaccines. So silly! 79.8% as of 16th June so 12 weeks for the under 40s is early September. Potential that this will be brought down to 8 weeks for all which could ring it into August just. I do feel that the younger population will drag it out a bit

Last two weeks of August still look plausible; 2nd dose rates are now starting to ease as expected, to reflect the decline in 1st dose rates from end of March, and if that continues down to 1.7-2.0% increase every 5 days I'd target 8-10 weeks from now. This also aligns with the minimum expected gap between doses. Most people over 50 have had their second dose already, so the 2nd dose rate will be dependent on ~18-50 yrs groups, which I think are likely to complete the course. My expectation is that the impact of the delta variant and summer travel requirements will offset any disincentives, and many wealthier families may even book second doses earlier to allow flights abroad (a small proportion but enough to keep a steady trend throughout July). Any slight slowing from this will clearly push things into September though, when the issue of holidays abroad is negated, so it is still quite open.
At current rates, it will be about 40 days until the target is reached (roughly 12 million doses remaining, at around 300k per day). That puts the end date around July 25th.
Strengthened estimate as trend is continuing
Updating based on the jab rate since this question opened, and based on the news today on jab strategy target.

Last two weeks of August still looks plausible to me, if 2nd doses decline to approx 30% from current rates from next week, beginning to mirror 1st dose rates and factoring in the delay between doses. Overall uptake across age-groups is consistently high, and this should be maintained due to delta strain concerns and issues with flying and travel requirements.

lots of calc here! 67.61M inhabitants in UK. based on 2018 stats (the most recent i found) 21.3% under 18 meaning 14.4M people leaving 53.21M over 18 to receive vaccination. currently 56.6% have received 2nd dose, 78.1% have received 1st dose which is getting close to 80% so therefore vaccine hesitancy (estimated at 7%) is unlikely to factor. 12.5M require vaccination to reach 80% with 2nd dose. vaccine rate of second dose is approx 300k per day, 1st dose is 174k per day. if we just consider 2nd dose rate (assuming no hiccups!) then 41 days to achieve 80% which would mean between July 1 and 31. if we assume 1st dose finishes and more vaccinators become available then rate might increase but not enough to move into June. what could go wrong: another variant which causes another lock down anti vaccers destroy lots of doses of vaccine failure of vaccine providers to deliver doses. - but lots of providers and lots of doses purchased

Second shots are slowing down slightly, but fairly steady. With first doses at 78.9% and still increasing, I think it's safe to say that we can expect 80% of the population to be interested in getting a second dose.

Updated forecast based on information kindly provided by @Eolienne. With 2nd dose booked at time of first dose and the extremely limited vaccine skepticism relative to USA (my frame of reference), it is looking like August is the expected. I'm still guessing we see more of a difficult time than what's been happening so far and that might push it into September.

29,165,140 as of June 10 (55.4%). Increasing at 338k/day (0.6%) which is consistent with last week but still below the 60% mark where past trend slowed. It was noted that the second does is booked with the first dose so and puts the 2nd dose at 8-9 weeks behind the first. 55.4pc now. This is 4pc in 7 days so 0.57pc per day. With 24.6pc to go at this rate it’s 43 days so would be about 25 July. So expect the second doses to start dropping off soon, which will push out the date for 80pc. 1st dose still at 78pc so need at least 8 weeks from the date we get to 80pc of first doses as need that 80pc 1st dose available for 2nd dose and 8 weeks is the minimum booking time between dose 1 and 2. So those going in now won’t be able to book second dose before 8 weeks from now. Expect 80pc in next week or so and 8 weeks from then is august.
Currently at 40m

49% at start of June. Rising about 20% in the month of May and April. Assuming the same momentum would reach 80% at mid July (49% + 20%/month x1.5 months). Though i would expect a slow down as most people eager to get a vaccination would have done so and will be more difficult to convince the remaining few. I assumed that start 15% will be added by the start of july = 65%, 10% by the start of august = 75%, 5% by the start of September.

extrapolation of data on https://coronavirus.data.gov.uk/details/vaccinations I think I surestimated ''between 1 august and 31 august 2021''

Scribbled some quick maths and suggests that we will hit 80% both doses in second week of August if vaccinations continue at same rate. Big shift to first doses will arrive in coming weeks which will slow the climb to 80%. My model is based off 200k second doses per day for next couple of months so will keep an eye on those rates and update accordingly.
Quick first assessment just to get on the board here. I'm not super familiar with the UK's policies regarding vaccines but have some reasonable ideas based on comparisons to the USA.

- July 1st impossible given 3 week minimum wait for second jab - July 31st 'effectively' impossible given the 8 week minimum likely wait (although that was only for AZ over 50s) - Baseline theoretically latest date would be 2 weeks after 80% first doses, however some won't get a second dose so that target needs to be increased slightly - Likely to hit 80% in ~2 weeks so mid september we might expect target to be hit as a baseline, and Delta variant news on requiring 2 doses likely to mean that only a small (2%?) fraction will not come forward for a second dose
I think if deaths start to increase over the next few weeks - that will prompt a speedier uptake. Young people seem keener than pundits expected to have the vaccine.
Using a linear projection from the april onwards data
Summer and end of lockdown (Stage 4) will make most people forget. It is unlikely to happen based on crowd psychology.

Based on current progress, 80% should have received first jab by mid June. Current approach is gap of 8 weeks between first and second jab which would suggest mid August for 2nd jab. Govt target is to offer first jab to all Uk adults by end of July - fear of variants will increase focus on first jabs as more vulnerable groups are fully vaccinated. So September looks far more likely than August for 80% 2nd dose. Residual vaccine scepticism will slow progress. Potential curve ball is if J&J (one dose) rolls out.

Based on current vaccination rates for first doses they would cover 80% of the adult population around 18th of June. While the current run rate (7day avg) for 2nd doses is high at around 356k per day. As i understand it there has to be a minimum gap of 8 weeks between doses which rules out July. Even if everything goes smoothly enough(ie no supply constraints and people turn up for their 2nd doses in 8 weeks(the upper limit here is 12 weeks), we should hit the 80% mark for 2nd doses in Mid August (Around 14th or 15th August)
Currently at 53.6% and rising steadily at 20% per month. We're well on target for the middle of July.
@Iwantatr8 @adamcohen9250 Exactly this. Though I anticipate take up will slow, increasing the risk it is pushed into Sept or even Oct.
First stab (jab?) at this:

I'm going to allow a slight drop-off in 2nd doses through late July as holiday/staycation season starts - not sure how much this will be affected by the desire to get the 2nd dose to allow foreign travel.

Projecting the 2nd dose line forward gets to July 16th for 80% of adult population with 2nd dose. Arguments for faster: - once 1st doses are done, 2nd doses can ramp up more - Govt probably putting more pressure to speed up because of variant concerns, and there is a possibility that England has a stockpile that it can accelerate through. - Under 40s second doses are being brought forward to 8-week window rather than 12-week, as were over 50s. This could also happen for younger age groups. Arguments for slower: - Possibly supply issues, but I don't know if that's plausible. - Maybe uptake issuess for younger age groups, but uptake has been very high so far.
